    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-08-11T14:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-08-11T14:00:00-05:00" n="592"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d592">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.515/706: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Chargé in the United Kingdom</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Atherton</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-08-11T15:00:00-04:00"
                            >August 11, 1935—3 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>206. Your 362, August 10, 1 p.m., third sentence. Did Leith-Ross initiate the
                    press conference or was he approached and subjected to <pb facs="0725" n="613"
                        xml:id="pg_613"/> leading questions? Did he say expressly that “American
                    Government had made no reply”?</p>
                <p>What is your estimate of his attitude and his purpose in saying to the press just
                    these things and of how far they are suggestive of Foreign Office attitude and
                    tactics?</p>
                <p>What reports of this conversation has the British press given and what
                    comments?</p>
                <p>Avoid disclosing that we have inquired.</p>
                <p>Prompt telegraphic reply requested.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
